    comment: "<p>JavaScript strings are represented using UTF-16 code units. Each code unit can be used to represent a code point in the <code>[U+0000, U+FFFF]</code> range. Code points beyond that range are represented by a surrogate pair.  </p>\n<p>In ES6 the notation has been simplified:</p>\n<pre><code>\\\\ represents U+1F332 (EVERGREEN TREE)\n\"\\u{1F332}\"==\"ğŸŒ²\"==\"\\uD83C\\uDF32\"\n</code></pre>\n<p>As with ES5, having multiple code units per code point means that <code>.length</code> is not reliable:</p>\n<pre><code>'ğŸŒ²ğŸŒ²ğŸŒ²'.length // length is 6\n</code></pre>\n<p>However in ES6 the string iterator can be used to loop over code <strong>points</strong> rather than code <strong>units</strong>:</p>\n<pre><code>for (let codePoint of 'ğŸŒ²âœˆâ¤') {\n  console.log(codePoint);\n}\n// 'ğŸŒ²'\n// 'âœˆ'\n// 'â¤'\n</code></pre>\n<p>Use <code>.codePointAt</code> to get the base-10 numeric representation of a code point at a given position in a string (indexed by code unit).</p>\n<pre><code>for (let codePoint of 'ğŸŒ²âœˆâ¤') {\n  console.log(codePoint.codePointAt(0));\n}\n/*\n127794 (EVERGREEN TREE)\n9992 (AIRPLANE)\n10084 (HEAVY BLACK HEART)\n*/\n</code></pre>\n",
